    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA321-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu viṉaimuṟṟi mīḷvāṉ tērppākaṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the one returning after having accomplished [his] work said to the charioteer.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA321">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            cennilap puṟaviṉ puṉmayirp puruvai</l>
<l>            pāṭiṉ ṟeṇmaṇit tōṭutalaip peyarak</l>
<l>            kāṉa mullaik kayavā yalarip</l>
<l>            pārppaṉa makaḷir cāraṟpuṟat taṇiyak</l>
<l>            kalcuṭar cēruṅ katirmāy mālaip</l>
<l>            pulleṉ vaṟumaṉai nōkki mella</l>
<l>            varuntuṅ kollō tiruntiḻai yarivai</l>
<l>            vallaik kaṭavumati tērē ceṉṟika</l>
<l>            kuruntaviḻ kuṟumpoṟai payiṉṟa</l>
<l>            peruṅkali mūtūr marantōṉ ṟummē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In the evening when the rays disappear, when the glow joins the stones<note place="foot">I.e., the sun joins the western mountains.</note></l>
<l>to adorn the backside of the slopes of brahmin women<note place="foot">Here we encounter a construction problem. The parallelism with line 2 as well as contents ask for <term xml:lang="ta">makaḷir</term> as the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">aṇiya</term>. But then we are stuck with <term xml:lang="ta">cāral puṟattu</term> - T.V.G.’s solution that the women put on the flowers on the backside of the slope is as adhoc as the version given above.</note></l>
<l>with deep-mouthed flowers of the forest jasmine,</l>
<l>while the herds with bells clear [and] sweet in song of the short-haired</l>
<l>sheep in the woodland with red soil gather together,</l>
<l>is she suffering,</l>
<l>softly, looking about the empty poor house,</l>
<l>the young woman with perfect jewels?</l>
<l>You strong one, urge the chariot! Go!</l>
<l>There appear the trees of our old village with big bustle,</l>
<l>dense on the short hills where the wild limes are opening.</l>
      </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
